Foreign Ministry spokesman on U.S. administration's decision
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Pyongyang, April 4 (KCNA) -- A spokesman for the DPRK Foreign Ministry answered a question put by KCNA today as regards the fact that the U.S. administration recently decided not to "certify" to the congress this year the DPRK's abiding by the DPRK-U.S. Agreed Framework (AF).
 He said: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is none of our business whether the U.S. administration "certifies" to its congress the DPRK's compliance with AF or not as it is an issue belonging to the United States' internal affairs. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 What should not be overlooked, however, is that this issue may tarnish the image of the DPRK which has sincerely implemented its commitments under the AF as it is intended to create false impression that the U.S. is unilaterally implementing the AF. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Through this issue Washington seeks to convince the international community that the U.S. is abiding by the AF and the DPRK is not complying with it. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK has allowed the IAEA inspectors' constant watch on its nuclear facilities after freezing them as required by the AF. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is none other than the United States that is not abiding by the AF in actuality. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It has seriously delayed the provision of light water reactors (lwrs) nor has properly delivered heavy oil to the DPRK despite its commitments under the AF. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. should take an emergency measure to compensate for the shortage of electricity caused by the delayed provision of lwrs and deliver heavy oil for this year on time. This is the bounden duty to be fulfilled by the U.S. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  It is quite natural for the DPRK to take a corresponding step unless such measures are taken.

U.S. urged to stop obstructing Mt. Kumgang tour
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, April 4 (KCNA) -- A spokesman for the Korean Asia-Pacific Peace Committee released a statement today assailing the United States for launching a new smear campaign against the DPRK.
 It says: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. congressional investigation bureau in a "Report on South Korea-U.S. Relations" recently submitted to the congress claimed that North Korea "used" the money paid for Mt. Kumgang tour for a military purpose and the Hyundai is believed to have provided funds to the DPRK in secrecy. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 This diatribe on the part of the U.S. is prompted by its intention to justify its attempt to provoke a new war on the Korean Peninsula and calm down the South Koreans' mounting anti-U.S. sentiment. It is also intended to force South Korea to buy more U.S.-made weapons and scotch the Mt. Kumgang tour, symbolic of inter-Korean cooperation, in a bid to bring the north-south relations back to those in the period of confrontation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Bush administration has worked hard to derail the tourism since the first day of its office. The tourism that started amidst great expectation and concern of the nation has now become lukewarm. It is entirely attributable to the U.S. trickery and plots. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 All these facts go to clearly prove once again that the U.S. is the most wicked sworn enemy of the Korean nation as it is not only hindering inter-Korean exchange and cooperation undertaken between Koreans in the spirit of the June 15 North-South Joint Declaration but also putting a stumbling block in the way of achieving Korea's reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 As the DPRK has clarified more than once, if the U.S. persists in its moves to hamstring Mt. Kumgang tour that was undertaken as part of inter-Korean non-governmental cooperation, that will only result in further heightening the Koreans' anti-U.S. sentiment and touch off stronger protest and denunciation among all the Koreans. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. is well advised to stop at once obstructing the Mt. Kumgang tour and behave with reason and discretion, though belatedly.
